You do NOT need to explicitly add a visibility filter or use @withVisibilityFilter/@withVisibility decorators to restrict properties to 'Read' visibility when a model is only used as the return result of an operation. TypeSpec's standard emitters (such as OpenAPI and HTTP) automatically apply Lifecycle visibility based on the context in which the model is used. Specifically, when a model is used as the response type of an operation (e.g., for GET), only properties marked with @visibility(Lifecycle.Read) will be included in the emitted schema. This is implicit and handled by the emitter, so you should simply annotate your model properties with the appropriate @visibility decorators, and the correct shape will be emitted for each operation context.

For example:

```typespec
model Example {
  @visibility(Lifecycle.Read)
  id: string;
  @visibility(Lifecycle.Create, Lifecycle.Read)
  name: string;
  description: string;
}

@route("/example")
interface Examples {
  @get read(@path id: string): Example;
}
```

In this case, the OpenAPI emitter will automatically generate a response schema for GET that only includes properties with Lifecycle.Read visibility. You only need to use @withVisibilityFilter or related templates if you want to create custom views or models outside of the standard operation context.

