The duplicate operation error in TypeSpec occurs because the HTTP emitter detects two operations with the same HTTP method and route, regardless of whether they use different models or property settings. In TypeSpec, versioning decorators like @added, @removed, and @renamedFrom are designed to help you evolve your API across versions, but they do not change the route or operation signature for the emitter. If you define two operations (e.g., 'getV1') with the same HTTP route in the same interface—even if they use different models for different versions—the emitter will treat them as duplicates and fail.

To resolve this, you should not duplicate the operation for each version. Instead, use versioning decorators on the model or property itself to indicate the change in the property constraint (such as the maximum value). For example, you can use @added or @removed on the property or model to specify when the change applies. If the constraint (e.g., maximum value) cannot be versioned directly, you may need to create a new model for the new version and use @renamedFrom to indicate the change, but ensure that only one operation per route exists in the interface, and the model is versioned appropriately.

If you need to change the model for a specific version, use the add/remove/rename pattern for the property or model, and decorate the operation to use the correct model for the target version. Do not duplicate the operation itself—this will always cause a duplicate operation error.

Here is a simplified example of how to version a property constraint in a model:

```typespec
model LeafCertificateConfiguration {
  validityPeriodInDays: int32 @maxValue(30);
  @added(Versions.v2025_11_01_preview)
  validityPeriodInDaysV2: int32 @maxValue(90);
}

@armResourceOperations
interface Policies {
  get is ArmResourceRead<LeafCertificateConfiguration>;
}
```

In this example, only one 'get' operation exists, and the model is versioned using property decorators. If you need to change the model entirely, use @renamedFrom on the model, not the operation, and ensure only one operation per route is present.

If you still encounter issues, review your interface to ensure you do not have multiple operations with the same route and method, and apply versioning decorators to models and properties, not to duplicate operations.

