actual.answer:
Yes, in TypeSpec you can create a stable API version that omits select properties, while allowing those properties to exist in multiple preview versions. The recommended approach is to use the @added and @removed decorators to precisely control which versions a property appears in. 

Here's how it works:
- When you introduce a property in a preview version, use @added(Versions.<preview_version>). This will include the property in that preview and all subsequent versions unless you explicitly remove it.
- To exclude the property from a stable version, use @removed(Versions.<stable_version>). This will remove the property from the stable version and all subsequent versions, unless you add it back with another @added decorator in a later preview.
- If you want the property to appear in multiple preview versions but not in any stable version, you must use @added and @removed in combination for each version transition.

For example, suppose you have preview versions 2024-11-01-preview, 2025-03-01-preview, 2025-06-01-preview, and 2025-07-01-preview, and stable versions in between. You can do:

```tsp
model MyResourceProperties {
  // Property appears in first preview
  @added(Versions.v2024_11_01_preview)
  @removed(Versions.v2025_03_01)
  faultSimulation?: FaultSimulationType;

  // Property reappears in next preview
  @added(Versions.v2025_03_01_preview)
  @removed(Versions.v2025_06_01)
  faultSimulation?: FaultSimulationType;

  // Property reappears in next preview
  @added(Versions.v2025_06_01_preview)
  @removed(Versions.v2025_07_01)
  faultSimulation?: FaultSimulationType;

  // Property reappears in latest preview
  @added(Versions.v2025_07_01_preview)
  faultSimulation?: FaultSimulationType;
}
```

This pattern ensures that faultSimulation is present only in the preview versions and omitted from all stable releases. However, this approach can be error-prone and verbose, so it's best to minimize the number of active preview versions. The official Azure policy is to have only one active preview version at a time, retiring older previews when a new one is introduced.

You can have multiple versions marked with @previewVersion, but only the latest preview should be active according to Azure guidelines. When you add a new preview, you should remove support for the previous preview soon after.

For more details and best practices, see the Azure TypeSpec versioning documentation and the example provided in the references.
